We've been going out every year to different eateries on Oahu for our anniversary and I figure we try this place out cause the reviews were pretty good.  So as a first timer here, we made reservation for 7pm dinner time.  We were promptly seated when we arrived. Our server (not sure of his name) greeted us and offered us the wine menu. Came back a few minutes later and asked if we needed help with anything, which we did.  He recommended some stuff but we still wasn't sure what to get.  Same goes for the dinner menu.  He explained what was what on the menu such as cold and hot food, soups, sushi, and hand rolls.  We decided to get a few drinks, their signature martini and some sake (not sure which one, forgot). As for the food we got the yellowtail jalapeño (winner), ahi uni (winner), salmon sashimi (winner), rack of lamb (winner), and pork belly (it was real soft, but was just ok). Overall food was great. As with every plate that came out, each one was explained to how it was made and what type of ingredient was used. Which as most fine dining restaurant will do the same.  No complaints here.  However our service was lack luster.  We ordered a few drinks but our waiter did not come by often to ask us if we need more drinks. We also had to ask for more water (not our waiter, but some other wait staff) a few times.  I also asked for a steak knife, cause it was hard to cut the rack of lamb with a butter knife.  So when our waiter did stop by I asked him if he had a steak knife. His answer was "I'm not sure we have any right now, but I will check". Ok which is fine, but he did not ever once come back and tell me that they have no knife what so ever.  Kept walking by our table and serving other tables near by us and not once mention anything to us. So we ended up just using a dull knife.  Overall for a first timer here, it wasn't a great experience. Especially if you're spending that type of money on food and service.  Food was great, service not so much.

When we arrived, we were immediately able to seat ourselves at a table of our choice at the covered patio.  My date had brought her dogs and it was no issue. Later, one of the waitstaff even brought water bowls for them.  When the waitstaff found out we had reservations, we were given the option to remain out on the patio for the time being as we had already ordered drinks (we had arrived at the tail end of happy hour) and appetizers.  While waiting for our order, we were offered sparkling water.  The appetizers, kurobuta andagi and Waygu manapua, did not have the expected texture associated with andagi and manapua. However, they were delicious nonetheless.  We ordered a second round, ahi poke and, our first "hot" dish, rock shrimp tempura with butter ponzu sauce.  As with the first, our second round of orders arrived in a short period of time.  The ahi had the firm flesh of freshness. Thinly sliced onions and a type of limu complimented the fish.  The rock shrimp tempura resembled popcorn shrimp. The shrimp was firm, the tempura batter crust light and crisp despite being already tossed with the rather savory sauce.  At this point, because of the growing chill, we asked to move to an indoor table. In a remarkably short time, our table was ready and we were escorted in. Our drinks followed us in and the inquiries about if we needed more water were frequent.  Our next orders were the kurobuta pork belly with Brussell sprouts and black cod with a miso sauce.  We had considered ordering one order each of the pork belly, but the waiter stated that the dish of 8 pieces could be an entree if accompanied with rice. I opted for a bowl of rice, my date did not.  The pieces of pork belly were savory, not greasy. The sprouts were tender and mild in flavor.  The black cod was slightly oily, but flaked readily.  At this point, we requested the dessert menu and coffee.  My date ordered the bento box, which arrived in an actual lacquered wooden box. Props for presentation there. The gelato was cold, smooth, and melted away quickly, leaving an aftertaste of matcha on the tongue.  I ordered the lemon crunch, which was a surprising variety of tastes and textures. The lemon custard was surprisingly sweet. The raspberry gelato tart and refreshing. The crunch seemed to have bits of dried sugared fruit. And nestled in the topping of whipped cream and chocolate shavings was a sugared ginger cookie.  Overall, our experience with the food and the service was an excellent one. Yes, it is expensive, but it is worth it. Would return, would recommend to family and friends.

We were blown away by the professionalism of the staff, quality of food, and hospitality by Chef Matt. We decided to splurge and ordered the Teppan experience and were not disappointed. My wife and I enjoyed the best meal of our lives thanks to Chef Matt. We even came back a few nights later to enjoy more food. Chef Matt remembered us and gave us a complementary order of Rock Shrimp. Thank you for an amazing experience.
IDIOT DE DUMMY!

A trendy restaurant with great tasting food and service to match. The staff is friendly and quick to assist. The decor is modern and the location at Ward is perfect. Plenty of parking. The restaurant is indoors with the bar and additional seating outdoors.

Cold and chic ambience and atmosphere. It was not busy when we went. The wait staff were very good to us. We were disappointed in the food. The rock shrimp tempura was the best, the crispy rice was good, but the spicy tuna that came with it was bland.  The poke bowl was good, but Simi's cafe in Gilbert, AZ makes better poke with more flavors for $10 and it's 10x the size. Overall expect a big bill and small supper. If you want great sushi, go to Yanagi Sushi!  Atmosphere is very different, but warm and extra cozy.

The absolutely fantastic restaurant for me! The best Japanese restaurant I’ve ever been in the world! The food is the art there. The world class service. Nobu is Nobu! The location is great. It is situated in Ward Village area where a lot of modern and trendy venues and shops are. I recommend it for residents and visitors of Hawaii. Even if you were in other Nobu restaurants around the world.
Food was great. The Sushi chefs were fairly friendly. The wait staff was good but not excellent. The atmosphere was elegant. I say its an absolut must in Oahu or NYC.

It was very disappointing and not what I expected for the high price. The $120 signature tasting menu included fish that tasted fishy (one day old raw fish), beef that didn’t taste fresh either, and ‘shave ice’ for dessert 🙄Yikes. Water & sugar syrup for dessert? Fruit would have been more exciting. My taste buds were overly underspoiled. A disappointing experience. I asked for another dessert and they created the ONLY thing that made me go ‘mmm’ in the end (that accommodation earned them an extra star), but had to let me know this would be a one time exception only, and that dessert was complimentary. So the $120 was basically just for the rest of the menu that I could have done better myself. I’m not coming back. I also had to ask for my green tea 3 times. That’s a record. The servers were shouting to each other in the back (close to our seating), it was displeasing to feel that rush of noise penetrate the scull on top of an already displeasing experience. I could make better food than what I had here. The surroundings are nice though, beautiful interior design! Go to Hoku’s instead; you’ll pay the same, and not go home disappointed.

(Translated by Google) I was looking forward to it in January, but I was very disappointed. What part of this store is being evaluated?  (Original) １月にとても楽しみにして行きましたが、とてもがっかりでした。このお店のどの部分が評価されているのでしょうか？

We were very disappointed that Nobu moved from its Waikiki location but still had to make a visit during our holiday and so glad we did. The new location is really gorgeous. Dramatic and beautiful.  We ordered the omakase and were not disappointed. Every dish was delicious and tasty. The white peach sangria is not on the menu anymore but they will still make it for you. It is still my favorite drink. So yummy.  The meal was delicious and I was in love with Nobu all over again. We make it a point to visit here as a treat every trip to Hawaii.

Eating at Nobu Honolulu is one of the best food experiences ever! It was our first time there, so we tried the Nobu Honolulu tasting.  It was about 7 courses of cold and hot plates.  The sushi and waguy beef were the best.  They both melted in your mouth.  The food is very fresh and prepared very well.  There is $7 valet parking right across the Buca Di Beppo restaurant and a nice walkway up to the main entrance to the restaurant.  Google maps directions needs to be a little fine tuned for this place.  It first directed us to the condo entrance of this building, Waiea.

Nobu Honolulu is my favourite Nobu. The food here is phenomenal, the drinks are fantastic, the atmosphere is cool, and the service is excellent. I've been to this restaurant many times, including when it was still Nobu Waikiki, and it never fails to please. The menu is innovative and the flavours are well thought out. Highly recommended!
Food is very good, service is not the best!

Favorite: Miso Butterfish, Jalapeno Hamachi, Salmon Sushi & Rock Shrimp with Spicy Cream Sauce. Pricey, but worth it when you wanna spoil yourself.

The Nobu empire reaches all corners of the globe.  The biggest challenge with a restaurant empire this big is consistency and quality control.  The original Nobu in Tribeca, New York when Matsuhisa was the Chef, before his global domination, will always be the gold standard.  The service is good but the consistency of the food could be improved.
Good food!

Delicious but pricy!
Great food, great service and beautiful atmosphere. You can never go wrong here. Yes it's a little pricey but your paying for unique dishes with amazing flavour.

Menu hasn’t changed much (ever??) but still good after 15+ years. Been in NY, Vegas, Milan, and now Honolulu. Definitely defines a category of restaurant that perhaps it started or at the very least made the biggest impact of any in the segment.  Shrimp appetizer, yellowtail jalapeño, sashimi salad, black cod, etc... all standbys. Haven’t had the Kobe beef in a while but that used to be phenomenal as well. Tried the steak cut into strips to share this visit, definitely enjoyable and good if you want just a taste of beef like the Kobe was.  A bit out of the way in Honolulu but I guess if you’re going to Nobu you’re not going to mind the extra time getting there.

Tried signature tasting menu. Everything was tasty and we were pretty full even before beef arrived. Service is quick, sometimes though waitress would start burning new dish and only then notices that plates from previous turn were not brought away. Ousters were better than in France!

Love this place! Anyone searching this restaurant in 2018 ought to take note that the address in wrong - it's NO longer at 2233 Helumoa Rd. in Waikiki's Parc Hotel. It has MOVED to 1118 Ala Moana Blvd. in the luxury residential tower, Waiea. Just saved you an Uber fare, thank me later.
AMAZING chocolate cake and fast service:) I recommend this place 1000000%

My bf, brother and I had the worst ever experience at this Nobu - we frequent the Nobu in Malibu and the Matsuhisa in West Hollywood on a weekly basis in la and cannot believe how atrocious the food was. We know Nobu and cannot believe a restaurant under his acclaimed name could be so poor. The manager was not helpful at all and had no widespread knowlegde of the dishes.  We were told we had to order 6 oz of Wagyu and that it would be completely plain which we were anticipating because of how amazing it is in LA - well we probably ate 2 oz worth due to how unflavorful and stale it was. The sashimi was served with skin on and all tasted like it went bad. All in all horrible experience if you've never been to a Nobu before and want to go for the "notoriety" of the restaurant then do so but know that if you want quality I would go elsewhere. We all feel sick.
Nice cocktails ($15) and dope apps, but Nobu prices...

The presentation was great and the wait staff were attentive and friendly.  Although the presentation was excellent, the quality of the food was not what I've expected from an upscale establishment with an upscale price.

Went during restaurant week to try something new and we really enjoyed ourselves. The service was great, the cocktails were unique and enjoyable, and the sake was so smooth. We liked the menu options that offered the option to try as many specialty dishes as possible. The Garlic shrimp was flavorful, the Tuna was fresh!, the Wagyu beef in any form (tacos/dish) was delicious and tender, as well as the sirloin with it's many sauce options. We were a lil rocked by the prices but felt the experience was well worth it!

At best average. Honestly the worst Nobu I’ve been to, including the landlocked Budapest. There are many better restaurants than this in Honolulu. Chef Nobu needs to focus on the consistency of his brand.  The sushi at our work cafeteria is prepared with more care, and the service was appalling. After not having seen our server for 30 minutes, the bus boy had to go and find him and reorder our food, after which we were double charged.  My advice is to look elsewhere.

If it wasn't the lack of flavor it was the consistency of the food: from tough and rubbery to improperly cooked. On top of all of this the portion sizes were stingy for the amount being spent. The only reason I gave any stars is because the wait staff.

Been to Nobu elsewhere, first time in Honolulu. Always had a 5 star experience until now. I took my date and we chose the exclusive chef special. Lobster was one of the courses and it was inedible. Like chewing rubber. The other 8 dishes were mediocre at best. Some completely flavorless. Overall, the experience was not worth the near $600. I will absolutely go back to Nobu in other cities, but never again in Honolulu. The chef did send a complimentary dish to make up for the lobster, which actually was the best one of all. So I certainly appreciate that. If this was a $150 dinner, it may have earned them an extra star, but in this case, 2 is a fair evaluation for my experience. I will give them a 5 star rating on presentation, but that unfortunately did not follow up with pleasant tastings. The wait staff were very attentive and kind.

The bar is set high with the Malibu location.  Food is good, service is very good, but ambience is lacking.  We'll continue to enjoy the Nobu experience, just not at this location.

Very nice and helpful jewelry store. They work with you to find out want kind of jewelry works for you and your budget.

Everything was very good not perfect. We got omakase. Very well served compared to others regular omakase, 4 cold dishes (yellow tail with ponzu, scalop ponzu sesame oil, sealed tuna salad, niguiri), 3 hot dishes (blackcod with miso, sealed ground beef with caramelized onions, soup). Best dish goes for Black cod, the fish was perfect, Sweet missô sauce, crispy radish, ginger root after to finish.😘 Worst thing i didn't like the "su" sauce that they use on rice. Overall ALL dishes were good not perfect but It was a good experience. Cost benefit (0 to 10) i would say 7 just because its very expensive.
Everything was amazing! The seabass was just unreal. Melt in your mouth! Be prepared to spend some money. The service is amazing as well.

Excellent food and customer service! Our server Ryan was very friendly, knowledgeable, and attentive. Everything he recommended was absolutely delicious! Nobu Honolulu is definitely the place to go for sushi and drinks. Highly recommend!

Where do I start?  We were a party of four and they wouldn't allow us to sit at the sushi bar even though it was empty the entire night.  We wanted to celebrate birthdays for two of us and ordered omakase for the entire group plus drinks and expensive sake.  Total bill was $1200.  Very underwhelming for the price paid.  We've eaten in many fine restaurants throughout the world including other Nobu locations.  Their brand has certainly gotten diluted and is no longer the unique experience they once were famous for.  The dishes weren't that unique or plentiful.  Their omakase cost $160 per person for 8 dishes. The wagu beef dish was the best of the group but hardly worth the price.  Next dish was a pretty typical cold soba dish we could find at a conventional $20 meal.  Service was ok but uninspired, no excitement or passion in their delivery.  For $300 per person, we expect a much higher quality and offering.  All in all, over priced and over hyped.

This is the worst omakase I've ever had. Nothing was amazing, creative, or memorable. Food was just done right. The first course was already the best and everything went downhill after. For $160 omakase, my friends who ordered a la carte with their signature dishes had better food than what was supposed to be the best selections from the chef. Just to name a few of the disappointments: the chives on the seared salmon was old, the dressing on the amber jack was over powering, and the wagyu was chewy. They sure know how to piss you off further though, because we got lava cake which anyone could make any day at home or from any franchise restaurant. I have never been so pissed after an omakase experience and I hope no one makes the same mistake and have to end a meal with such feelings. Please see photos.
Worst service ever, our party was finishing eating before everybody in the table was still ordering. Useless manager, very desorganized.

We had a nine person omakase which was out of this world amazing.  Twelve courses that were expertly presented and ordered to give us one of the best taste experiences we've ever had.
Always amazing and expensive -- although, so bummed that they moved out of the Parc Hotel.
Great Nobu classics plus new items. Sake, cocktail and wine options are great. Sushi is of course top-notch.
Value is just not there.   Food is definitely good, but there is much better sushi for half the price in the city.

Two and a half stars honestly. Food was hit or miss with some fantastic did and some items that were merely OK. The service was a definite miss, especially for the price point of the restaurant.  The table was cleared slowly and sloppily between courses. Our drinks languished empty. Come desert, my wife had her teapot top open to signal for more hot water and the waiter took the teapot never returning it. When my wife asked the waiter then went into a long digression that didn't culminate in "Sorry let me grab you some more tea."  This ended our otherwise OK meal on a sour note. Then to top of the evening, the waiter kindly circled the gratuity guide which happened to run from 18% - 22% which was a bit humorous since even by US standards the service we received was at best 15%.  I certainly hope the restaurant improves, but I can't recommend them at this time.
awesome place

Beautiful decor..check..attentive service...check...fabulous food? Forget it! I had no idea how overpriced this place was until I sat down and they handed me the menu!  Still, I thought its Christmas Eve so treat yourself!  Well $93 later (including tip) I had eaten a Nigiri roll which was no bigger round than my thumb and was supposed to have unagi (freshwater eel) in it but somehow it got lost in the cucumber for $14 and a small piece of black cod..  delicious yes but at $39 was at least $10 overpriced add in a $14 drink and a bowl of rice and wham bam youre out over $70...add in the tip and its up to over $90.  I have eaten lots of Japanese food in the last 40 years in the LA area and other places and its usually not cheap but this place was just not satisfying.  I couldnt help but notice that there were no Asians in sight other than the wait staff either.  Never a "good sign" in an Asian restaurant!

The service is very friendly.  The ambiance was really fun and it really added to the atmosphere of the restaurant.  We did the tasty omakaze menu and it was really delicious.  Fresh ingredients.  They also had a great selection of drinks.  Really great place if you are celebrating a special occasion.

Far too expensive. It's ok food, but no better than many upscale Japanese restaurants. Waiters constantly try to upsell you - "do you want to add sea urchin on your scallop?" Without telling you it costs more than the entire original dish

Great restaurant tucked in a neat little core we of Waikiki. The crowds are small and I would say that the prices are decent for the quality of food. I have been back multiple times and enjoy everything about it each time I go.

Let's start with the Valet Parking. It took us circling a dead end street that took us in front of Parc Hotel three times before anyone approached us. We even stopped the first two times in hopes of someone coming out of the cracks to aid in our journey. Once inside, we were greeted by a very young and unprofessional hostess staff. Once seated, the waitress asked us if we wanted drinks. She then waited on the table next to us as. She left then came back to the table next to us and started explaining the menu to the two ladies. We were then approached by a waiter who asked if we wanted drinks. After explaining to him that we had already been waited on, he explained that he would be waiting on us. The menu was explained to us from the top priced item, then a very small trickle as to what else was available. Of which were equally priced. I expressed my frustration with no real feedback. We came to the restaurant for sushi and heard how amazing it was. After researching the restaurant I realized the founder was a sushi chef and raved about how important it was to bring his expertise into a market that was saturated and took great pride in what he could produce with credentials added. Ummm... The sushi was much of what one would expect to purchase in a prepackaged selection of sushi in a grocery store chain. Although the hot and spicy seafood soup was stellar and satisfying. The waiter was an amateur in handling the situation with nothing more than a deer in the headlights response. Paid our bill with a substantial tip for the mere fact of morale. Two thumbs down.
My wife and I got the Omakase here. It was amazing. Best dinner in Hawaii.
The food is great, like other Nobu locations; however, I was not impressed by the location or decor. The restaurant is located inside a hotel on a street lined with other tall hotels.

I came here for my birthday last year while vacationing in Waikiki. I've personally never been to any of the Nobu restaurants, and usually prefer to go to Morimoto, but all my friends insisted I go, and raved about this place.  For starters, we had the Nobu tacos, they were just okay, sort of bland; nothing too special to write home about.  My boyfriend had the omakase and I ordered a few extra items from the menu. None of the dishes really stood out to me, besides the rock shrimp. I enjoyed the presentation more than the meal, sadly.  The ambiance was nice, but I'm not sure I'd come again next time I'm on the island. Going to Morimoto instead ;)

The Nobu Waikiki is a unique and modern style of Japanese restaurant which combines fair Asian cuisines with great vibes. Prior to our dinner reservations at the Nobu, we actually wanted to dine at Alan Wong's Restaurant, but unfortunately, we were told by the RH concierge that the Alan Wong's Restaurant were fully booked, therefore, we decided to dine at Nobu knowing the restaurant is also one of President Obama's favorites and we wanted to give it a try.  While the Nobu was indeed quite trendy and modern, with some freshly made cuisines, namely, seafood cerviche and new style salmon for appetizers, black cod miso, duck breast and assortment of sushi plus some single orders of sashimis, as recommended by our waiter, but I found the serving size a little disconcerting – simply put, portions were just too small. In addition, the service was not very Hawaiian, everything was rushed, and one of my relatives needed to chase down the waiter a few times just to get refills for her soda.  Overall, I would say the serving size and the level of service based on dollar-value of the meal were disappointing in this regard.
Best sushi I have ever had. It was my first time trying Nobu as there an none here in Australia. Warning: it does cost a lot, but I would highly recommend it as it is amazing.
Outstanding food, service, and atmosphere. Perfectly attentive waitstaff, sublime food. Meticulous attention to detail. In the top 1% of all restaurants in Hawaii. No exaggeration.

Very attractive, dark space.  We chose to eat in the bar.  Both the sushi and the small plates we tried were delicious, as were the drinks, and the service was good.  We left just in time before the see-and-be-seen crowd got too annoying.

We are big Nobu fans - have been to LA and Melbourne and enjoyed both.  But here things were a bit less dazzle.  The salmon tartare was a highlight - minced and swimming in wasabi.  But the other choices were good not great and we know he can be great.   The mushroom/conch was great if you love mushrooms - with a hint of conch.   The wine list is distinctly lackluster!   The room feels a bit chintzy too, though at least there's room btwn tables.
the food is quite good, but if you're looking for the best sushi on the island you should head to sasabune.  this place is quite trendy and a bit overpriced.
